data.value:
As the planet closest to the sun, Mercury tends to get a lot of heat. In fact, surface temperatures on Mercury can reach a blistering 840 degrees Fahrenheit! This means that the planet is hot enough to melt certain metals, like tin. While Mercury gets unbelievably hot during its day cycle, nights are another story. This world doesn’t have a real atmosphere to entrap heat, so nighttime temperatures can get as low as negative 275 degrees fahrenheit.
This lack of an atmosphere has other effects- namely, asteroids and meteors. With no atmosphere to stop impacts, the planet’s surface is pockmarked with craters.
Due to its proximity to the sun, Mercury also boasts the record for fastest planet. In a whopping 87.97 Earth days, Mercury can complete its entire revolution around the sun. In comparison it takes 59 Earth days for one day on mercury. Mercury is only slightly larger than the Earth’s moon, making it the smallest planet in our solar system.
Mercury is named after the Roman God Mercury, who was the god of financial gain, commerce, eloquence, messages, travelers, luck, trickery and thievery. His Greek name is Hermes, the messenger god.
